.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/12px-Red_pog.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/16px-Red_pog.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="64" data-file-height="64" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:5px;left:-3em;text-align:center"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px"><small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khabarovsk" title="Khabarovsk">Khabarovsk</a></small></div></div></div><div style="position:absolute;top:89.958%;left:78.435%"><div style="position:absolute;left:-4px;top:-4px;line-height:0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladivostok" title="Vladivostok"><img alt="alt text for Vladivostok" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/City_locator_26.svg/8px-City_locator_26.svg.png" decoding="async" width="8" height="8" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/City_locator_26.svg/12px-City_locator_26.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/City_locator_26.svg/16px-City_locator_26.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="10" data-file-height="10" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:-0.75em;left:5px;text-align:left"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px;float:left"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladivostok" title="Vladivostok">Vladivostok</a></div></div></div><div style="position:absolute;top:43.538%;left:79.471%"><div style="position:absolute;left:-4px;top:-4px;line-height:0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magadan" title="Magadan"><img alt="alt text for Magadan" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/8px-Red_pog.svg.png" decoding="async" width="8" height="8" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/12px-Red_pog.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/16px-Red_pog.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="64" data-file-height="64" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:-0.75em;right:5px;text-align:right"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px;float:right"><small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magadan" title="Magadan">Magadan</a></small></div></div></div><div style="position:absolute;top:73.356%;left:84.352%"><div style="position:absolute;left:-4px;top:-4px;line-height:0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk" title="Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk"><img alt="alt text for Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/8px-Red_pog.svg.png" decoding="async" width="8" height="8" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/12px-Red_pog.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/16px-Red_pog.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="64" data-file-height="64" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:-0.75em;left:5px;text-align:left"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px;float:left"><small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk" title="Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk">Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk</a></small></div></div></div><div style="position:absolute;top:47.379%;left:89.046%"><div style="position:absolute;left:-4px;top:-4px;line-height:0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky" title="Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky"><img alt="alt text for Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/8px-Red_pog.svg.png" decoding="async" width="8" height="8" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/12px-Red_pog.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/16px-Red_pog.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="64" data-file-height="64" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:5px;left:-3em;text-align:center"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px"><small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky" title="Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky">Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky</a></small></div></div></div><div style="position:absolute;top:21.788%;left:4.096%"><div style="position:absolute;left:-4px;top:-4px;line-height:0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaliningrad_Oblast" title="Kaliningrad"><img alt="alt text for Kaliningrad" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/8px-Red_pog.svg.png" decoding="async" width="8" height="8" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/12px-Red_pog.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/16px-Red_pog.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="64" data-file-height="64" /></a></div><div style="font-size:90%;line-height:110%;position:absolute;width:6em;top:-0.75em;left:5px;text-align:left"><div style="display:inline;padding:1px;float:left"><small><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaliningrad_Oblast" title="Kaliningrad Oblast">Kaliningrad</a></small></div></div></div></div><div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Russia_edcp_relief_location_map.jpg" title="File:Russia edcp relief location map.jpg"> </a></div><div class="center" style="width:auto; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;">Physical map of Russia with locations of major cities</div></div></div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:442px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg/440px-Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg.png" decoding="async" width="440" height="206" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg/660px-Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg/880px-Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1816" data-file-height="850" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Koppen-Geiger_Map_RUS_present.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification" title="Köppen climate classification">Köppen climate types</a> of Russia</div></div></div>
<p>Russia is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Largest_country_in_the_world" class="mw-redirect" title="Largest country in the world">largest country in the world</a>; its total area is 17,075,200 square kilometres (6,592,800&#160;sq&#160;mi).<sup id="cite_ref-General_Information_190-0" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-General_Information-190">&#91;186&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-area_191-0" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-area-191">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup> This makes it larger than the continents of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oceania" title="Oceania">Oceania</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">Antarctica</a>. It lies between latitudes <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/41st_parallel_north" title="41st parallel north">41°</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/82nd_parallel_north" title="82nd parallel north">82° N</a>, and longitudes <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/19th_meridian_east" title="19th meridian east">19° E</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/169th_meridian_west" title="169th meridian west">169° W</a>.
</p><p>Russia's territorial expansion was achieved largely in the late 16th century under the Cossack <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yermak_Timofeyevich" title="Yermak Timofeyevich">Yermak Timofeyevich</a> during the reign of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_the_Terrible" title="Ivan the Terrible">Ivan the Terrible</a>, at a time when competing city-states in the western regions of Russia had banded together to form one country. Yermak mustered an army and pushed eastward where he conquered nearly all the lands once belonging to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongol_Empire" title="Mongol Empire">Mongols</a>, defeating their ruler, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuchum" title="Kuchum">Khan Kuchum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-192" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-192">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Russia has a wide natural resource base, including major deposits of timber, petroleum, natural gas, coal, ores and other mineral resources.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Topography">Topography</span></h3>
<p>The two most widely separated points in Russia are about 8,000&#160;km (4,971&#160;mi) apart along a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geodesic" title="Geodesic">geodesic</a> line. These points are: a 60&#160;km (37&#160;mi) long <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vistula_Spit" title="Vistula Spit">Vistula Spit</a> the boundary with Poland separating the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gda%C5%84sk_Bay" title="Gdańsk Bay">Gdańsk Bay</a> from the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vistula_Lagoon" title="Vistula Lagoon">Vistula Lagoon</a> and the most southeastern point of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuril_Islands" title="Kuril Islands">Kuril Islands</a>. The points which are farthest separated in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitude" title="Longitude">longitude</a> are 6,600&#160;km (4,101&#160;mi) apart along a geodesic line. These points are: in the west, the same spit on the boundary with Poland, and in the east, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Diomede_Island" class="mw-redirect" title="Big Diomede Island">Big Diomede Island</a>. The Russian Federation spans 11 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_zone" title="Time zone">time zones</a>.
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg/220px-Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg/330px-Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg/440px-Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3008" data-file-height="2000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mount_Elbrus_May_2008.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Elbrus" title="Mount Elbrus">Mount Elbrus</a>, a dormant volcano, is the highest mountain in Europe, Russia, the Caucasus and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_mountain_peaks_by_prominence" title="List of mountain peaks by prominence">tenth-most prominent peak</a> in the world.</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg/220px-Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="145" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg/330px-Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg/440px-Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3332" data-file-height="2200" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Volga_River_P8132394_2200.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volga_River" class="mw-redirect" title="Volga River">Volga River</a> at <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nizhny_Novgorod_Oblast" title="Nizhny Novgorod Oblast">Nizhny Novgorod</a>. It is the longest river in Europe.</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_(24231533812).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg/220px-Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="137" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg/330px-Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg/440px-Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_%2824231533812%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5874" data-file-height="3671" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kamchatka_Volcano_Koryaksky_(24231533812).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koryaksky" title="Koryaksky">Koryaksky</a> volcano towering over <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky" title="Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky">Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky</a> on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamchatka_Peninsula" title="Kamchatka Peninsula">Kamchatka Peninsula</a></div></div></div>
<p>Most of Russia consists of vast stretches of plains that are predominantly <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steppe" title="Steppe">steppe</a> to the south and heavily forested to the north, with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tundra" title="Tundra">tundra</a> along the northern coast. Russia possesses 10% of the world's <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arable_land" title="Arable land">arable land</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-193">&#91;189&#93;</a></sup> Mountain ranges are found along the southern borders, such as the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caucasus_Mountains" title="Caucasus Mountains">Caucasus</a> (containing <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Elbrus" title="Mount Elbrus">Mount Elbrus</a>, which at 5,642&#160;m (18,510&#160;ft) is the highest point in both Russia and Europe) and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altai_Mountains" title="Altai Mountains">Altai</a> (containing <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Belukha" class="mw-redirect" title="Mount Belukha">Mount Belukha</a>, which at the 4,506&#160;m (14,783&#160;ft) is the highest point of Siberia outside of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_Far_East" title="Russian Far East">Russian Far East</a>); and in the eastern parts, such as the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verkhoyansk_Range" title="Verkhoyansk Range">Verkhoyansk Range</a> or the volcanoes of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamchatka_Peninsula" title="Kamchatka Peninsula">Kamchatka Peninsula</a> (containing <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klyuchevskaya_Sopka" title="Klyuchevskaya Sopka">Klyuchevskaya Sopka</a>, which at the 4,750&#160;m (15,584&#160;ft) is the highest <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Active_volcano" class="mw-redirect" title="Active volcano">active volcano</a> in Eurasia as well as the highest point of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asian_Russia" class="mw-redirect" title="Asian Russia">Asian Russia</a>). The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ural_Mountains" title="Ural Mountains">Ural Mountains</a>, rich in mineral resources, form a north–south range that divides Europe and Asia.
</p><p>Russia has an extensive coastline of over 37,000&#160;km (22,991&#160;mi) along the Arctic and Pacific Oceans, as well as along the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baltic_Sea" title="Baltic Sea">Baltic Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Azov" title="Sea of Azov">Sea of Azov</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Sea" title="Black Sea">Black Sea</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caspian_Sea" title="Caspian Sea">Caspian Sea</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cia_126-2" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-cia-126">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barents_Sea" title="Barents Sea">Barents Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Sea" title="White Sea">White Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kara_Sea" title="Kara Sea">Kara Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laptev_Sea" title="Laptev Sea">Laptev Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Siberian_Sea" title="East Siberian Sea">East Siberian Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chukchi_Sea" title="Chukchi Sea">Chukchi Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bering_Sea" title="Bering Sea">Bering Sea</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Okhotsk" title="Sea of Okhotsk">Sea of Okhotsk</a>, and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Japan" title="Sea of Japan">Sea of Japan</a> are linked to Russia via the Arctic and Pacific. Russia's major islands and archipelagos include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Novaya_Zemlya" title="Novaya Zemlya">Novaya Zemlya</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Josef_Land" title="Franz Josef Land">Franz Josef Land</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Severnaya_Zemlya" title="Severnaya Zemlya">Severnaya Zemlya</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Siberian_Islands" title="New Siberian Islands">New Siberian Islands</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrangel_Island" title="Wrangel Island">Wrangel Island</a>, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuril_Islands" title="Kuril Islands">Kuril Islands</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakhalin" title="Sakhalin">Sakhalin</a>. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diomede_Islands" title="Diomede Islands">Diomede Islands</a> (one controlled by Russia, the other by the United States) are just 3&#160;km (1.9&#160;mi) apart, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kunashir_Island" title="Kunashir Island">Kunashir Island</a> is about 20&#160;km (12.4&#160;mi) from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hokkaido" title="Hokkaido">Hokkaido</a>, Japan.
</p><p>Russia has thousands of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivers_in_Russia" class="mw-redirect" title="Rivers in Russia">rivers</a> and inland bodies of water, providing it with one of the world's largest surface water resources. Its lakes contain approximately one-quarter of the world's liquid <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fresh_water" title="Fresh water">fresh water</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-loc_194-0" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-loc-194">&#91;190&#93;</a></sup> The largest and most prominent of Russia's bodies of fresh water is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Baikal" title="Lake Baikal">Lake Baikal</a>, the world's deepest, purest, oldest and most capacious fresh water lake.<sup id="cite_ref-baikal_195-0" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-baikal-195">&#91;191&#93;</a></sup> Baikal alone contains over one-fifth of the world's fresh surface water.<sup id="cite_ref-loc_194-1" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-loc-194">&#91;190&#93;</a></sup> Other major lakes include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Ladoga" title="Lake Ladoga">Ladoga</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Onega" title="Lake Onega">Onega</a>, two of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Largest_lakes_in_Europe" class="mw-redirect" title="Largest lakes in Europe">largest lakes in Europe</a>. Russia is second only to Brazil in volume of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_renewable_water_resources" class="mw-redirect" title="Total renewable water resources">total renewable water resources</a>. Of the country's 100,000 rivers,<sup id="cite_ref-196" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-196">&#91;192&#93;</a></sup> the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volga" title="Volga">Volga</a> is the most famous, not only because it is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longest_river_in_Europe" class="mw-redirect" title="Longest river in Europe">longest river in Europe</a>, but also because of its major role in Russian history.<sup id="cite_ref-cia_126-3" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-cia-126">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> The Siberian rivers <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ob_River" class="mw-redirect" title="Ob River">Ob</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yenisey" title="Yenisey">Yenisey</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lena_River" class="mw-redirect" title="Lena River">Lena</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amur_River" class="mw-redirect" title="Amur River">Amur</a> are among the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longest_rivers_in_the_world" class="mw-redirect" title="Longest rivers in the world">longest rivers in the world</a>.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Climate">Climate</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_of_Russia" title="Climate of Russia">Climate of Russia</a></div>
<p>The enormous size of Russia and the remoteness of many areas from the sea result in the dominance of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humid_continental_climate" title="Humid continental climate">humid continental climate</a>, which is prevalent in all parts of the country except for the tundra and the extreme southwest. Mountains in the south obstruct the flow of warm air masses from the Indian Ocean, while the plain of the west and north makes the country open to Arctic and Atlantic influences.<sup id="cite_ref-congress_197-0" class="reference"><a href="Russia#cite_note-congress-197">&#91;193&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Most of Northern European Russia and Siberia has a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarctic_climate" title="Subarctic climate">subarctic climate</a>, with extremely severe winters in the inner regions of Northeast Siberia (mostly the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakha_Republic" class="mw-redirect" title="Sakha Republic">Sakha Republic</a>, where the Northern <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pole_of_Cold" title="Pole of Cold">Pole of Cold</a> is located with the record low temperature of −71.2&#160;°C or −96.2&#160;°F), and more moderate winters elsewhere. Both the strip of land along the shore of the Arctic Ocean and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_Arctic_islands" title="Russian Arctic islands">Russian Arctic islands</a> have a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_climate" title="Polar climate">polar climate</a>.
</p><p>The coastal part of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krasnodar_Krai" title="Krasnodar Krai">Krasnodar Krai</a> on the Black Sea, most notably in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sochi" title="Sochi">Sochi</a>, possesses a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humid_subtropical_climate" title="Humid subtropical climate">humid subtropical climate</a> with mild and wet winters. In many regions of East Siberia and the Far East, winter is dry compared to summer; other parts of the country experience more even precipitation across seasons. Winter precipitation in most parts of the country usually falls as snow. The region along the Lower Volga and Caspian Sea coast, as well as some areas of southernmost Siberia, possesses a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semi-arid_climate" title="Semi-arid climate">semi-arid climate</a>.
</p>
<div>
